{
  "answer": "**Gham** (deep, brooding, heart-consuming sorrow): In Allama Iqbal's \"Parinde Ki Faryad,\" the bird's lament captures *gham* as a reciprocal, all-devouring grief born of captivity and loss, where heart and sorrow mutually erode each other—like acid eating flesh from within. \"Dil *gham* ko kha raha hai, *gham* dil ko kha raha hai\" (\"My heart is consuming its grief... And grief is consuming my heart\").[^1] Substituting *ranj* (a sharper relational wound) loses the slow, existential mutuality; *azaab* (punitive torment) implies external hellfire, not this internal corrosion.\n\n**Ranj** (wounded resentment, insufficiently soothed pain): Ghalib's opening sher in his ghazal contrasts the ambient \"gham khaane\" (tavern of grief) with personal *ranj*, a nagging ache that even roseate wine barely touches—highlighting *ranj*'s intimate, stubborn bitterness amid collective woe. \"Gham khaane mein boda dil-e-nakaam bahut hai / Yeh *ranj* ke kam hai mai-e-gulfaam bahut hai\" (\"This weak, failed heart's capacity for pain is more than enough; The grief that rose-red wine is on the wane is more than enough\").[^2] Swap to *gham* and it redundantly echoes the venue; *azaab* overheats it into infernal agony, unfit for wine's mild balm.\n\n**Azaab** (scorching, paradoxical torment): Ghalib revels in *azaab* as lover-inflicted hell where relief (*raahat*) bizarrely resides—fire from her scent, yet comfort in the blaze itself, evoking masochistic ecstasy. \"Milti hai khuu-e-yaar se naar iltihaab mein / Kaafir hoon gar na milti ho raahat *azaab* mein\" (\"Her very nature is a burning fire, in this despair. A heathen I, if I find no strange comfort... in this despair\").[^3] *Gham* chills it to melancholy; *ranj* dulls to mere pique—neither sustains the infernal rapture.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, \"Parinde Ki Faryad\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/34-parinde-ki-faryad/translation/#p-51fe7d).\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, \"Gham khaane mein boda dil-e-nakaam bahut hai\" [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/50-gham-khaane-mein-boda-dil-e-nakaam-bahut-hai/translation/#p-b39b6a).\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, \"Milti hai khuu-e-yaar se naar iltihaab mein\" [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/138-milti-hai-khuu-e-yaar-se-naar-iltihaab-mein/translation/#p-2eef4c).",
